   <titles>
      <title>Subvector space - Illustration</title>
   </titles>
   <body>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>A subvector space of <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                  </math> is a collection of vectors <math>
                     <latex>V</latex>
                  </math> containing the 0-vector and which is closed under vector addition and scalar multiplication of a vector in <math>
                     <latex>V</latex>
                  </math> by a number. Here is a visual interpretation of what this means.</para.body>
            </para>
            <ul>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>If <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                        </math> and <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                        </math> are vectors in <math>
                           <latex>V</latex>
                        </math>, then <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{x}+\Vect{y}</latex>
                        </math> is also in <math>
                           <latex>V</latex>
                        </math>.</para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>If <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                        </math> is a vector in <math>
                           <latex>V</latex>
                        </math>, and <math>
                           <latex>t</latex>
                        </math> is a number, then <math>
                           <latex>t \Vect{x}</latex>
                        </math> is also in <math>
                           <latex>V</latex>
                        </math>.</para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
            </ul>
            <media xmlns="Theorem" type="image" active="0" inline="0">
               <img xmlns="" src="ims/SubSpaceClosedAddition.gif"/>
            </media>
            <media xmlns="Theorem" type="image" active="0" inline="0">
               <img xmlns="" src="ims/SubSpaceClosedScalarMultiplication.gif"/>
            </media>
         </block.body>
      </block>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>In contrast, here is a subset <math>
                     <latex>V</latex>
                  </math> of <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                  </math> which is not a subvector space.</para.body>
            </para>
            <media xmlns="Theorem" type="image" active="0" inline="0">
               <img xmlns="" src="ims/SubSetNotClosedAddition.gif"/>
            </media>
            <para>
               <para.body>Indeed, there are (at least) two vectors <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                  </math> in <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                  </math> whose sum <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{x} + \Vect{y}</latex>
                  </math> is not in <math>
                     <latex>V</latex>
                  </math>; i.e. this line is not closed under vector addition, hence is not a subvector space.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
   </body>
